'''Crime in Bolivia''' is investigated by the [[Law enforcement in Bolivia|Bolivian police]].

== Crime by type ==

=== Murder ===
{{Further|List of countries by intentional homicide rate}}

In 2012, Bolivia had a murder rate of 12.1 per 100,000 population.<ref name=UNODC/> There were a total of 1,270 murders in Bolivia in 2012.<ref name=UNODC>[https://www.unodc.org/gsh/en/index.html ''Global Study on Homicide''. [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]], 2013.]</ref>

=== Illegal drug trade ===
{{Further|Illegal drug trade in Bolivia}}

The Bolivian government has since 2004 implemented a policy of voluntary participation of farmers from all coca-growing regions in Bolivia. For instance, farmers in Chapare are allowed to grow one cato of coca per year.<ref name=Ledebur>{{cite journal | last1 = Ledebur | first1 = K. | last2 = Youngers | first2 = C. | year = 2013 | title = From Conflict to Collaboration: An Innovative Approach to Reducing Coca Cultivation in Bolivia | url = | journal = Stability: International Journal of Security and Development | volume = 2 | issue = 1| page = 9 | doi = 10.5334/sta.aw }}</ref> Any coca grown beyond that limit, or any cultivation outside of approved coca-cultivation regions such as Chapare, is subject to elimination. The strategy relies on coca growers federations’ ability to enforce the agreement. Such federations are influential, and penalties for violations by farmers or lax enforcement by federations can be stern (including seizure of lands). As a result, coca cultivation in Bolivia fell to 27,200 hectares in 2011 from 31,000 hectares in 2010 - a 12 per cent decrease.<ref name=Ledebur />

=== Domestic violence ===
{{Further|Domestic violence in Bolivia}}
[[Domestic violence]] is a serious and underreported problem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/humanrightsreport/index.htm#section6|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2016|website=www.state.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref> According to the Center for the Women’s Information and Development (CIDEM) and Emancipation Fund study, the number of reported domestic violence cases increased by 37% between 2007 and 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/humanrightsreport/index.htm#section6women|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2016|website=www.state.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref> A study by the [[Pan American Health Organization]] conducted in 12 Latin American countries found the highest prevalence of domestic violence against women to be in Bolivia.<ref>http://www2.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf</ref>

