{{About|the ethnic slur|the headdress|Gook (headgear)|the river in the United States|Gook Creek|the film|Gook (film)}} '''''Gook''''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|uː|k}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|ʊ|k}}) is a derogatory term for certain people of [[East Asians|East]] and [[Southeast Asian]] descent. The slur is frequently directed toward foreigners, especially people of Filipino, Korean, or Vietnamese descent.<ref>''[https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/gook Oxford Dictionares]''</ref> It was originally predominantly used by the U.S. military during wartime, especially during the [[Korean War|Korean War]], and more so during the [[Vietnam War|Vietnam War]].<ref name=roegook>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidroediger.org/articles/gook-the-short-history-of-americanism.html |title=Gook: The Short History of an Americanism |work=[[Monthly Review]] |date=March 1992 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030111334/http://www.davidroediger.org/articles/gook-the-short-history-of-americanism.html |archivedate=October 30, 2014 }}</ref><ref>http://www.dictionary.com/browse/gook?s=t</ref>
== Etymology and use == The ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' states that the origin of the current usage is unknown.<ref name=roegook /> There are three suggested possible origins: * An earlier usage of ''gook'', meaning "[[prostitute]]", recorded in a slang dictionary published in 1893, which defined ''gook'' as "a low prostitute";<ref name=farmer>{{cite book |last1=Farmer |first=John S. |last2=Henley |first2=W. E. |url=https://archive.org/stream/slangitsanalogue03farmuoft#page/181/mode/1up |title=Slang and its Analogues, Past and Present |publisher=Printed for subscribers only |date=1893 |volume=III - Fla. to Hyps. |page=181}}</ref> a similar meaning was recorded for ''gooh'' in 1859.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lighter |first=Jonathan E. |title=Random Historical Dictionary of American Slang |publisher=[[Random House]] |date=1997}}</ref> This later came to imply a foolish or peculiar person.<ref name=enswear /> The ''goo-goo'' term, whose origins are similarly uncertain, was first used in 1842 by U.S. troops in the [[Second Opium War]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Paterson |first=Thomas |last2=Merrill |first2=Dennis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=spA88Rt23soC&pg=PA389#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Major Problems in American Foreign Relations, Volume I |publisher=[[Cengage Learning]] |date=2009 |page=389}}</ref> to refer to Koreans living in China at the time, although ''slanty [[nigger]]'' was more prevalent to distinguish Koreans from the Chinese, who were referred to as ''chinky'' or ''chinks''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Unoki |first=Ko |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UaeL64p-ukC&ots=0oYh99XlTQ&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Mergers, Acquisitions and Global Empires |publisher=Routledge |date=2013 |page=87}}</ref> * That when American servicemen heard the term during the [[Korean War]], they heard the word as 'gook" instead of k(g)uk which means "national" (maybe, thus, interpreted as [[nationalist]]) ''goo-goo'' (also ''gugu''), a term used by the U.S. military to describe Koreans.<ref name=enswear>{{cite book |last=Hughes |first=Geoffrey |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2lHwkWMXaxwC&pg=PA207#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=An Encyclopedia of Swearing |publisher=[[Routledge]] |date=2006 |pages=207–8}}</ref> * That "gook" comes from the [[Korean language|Korean]] word "국" (''guk''), meaning "country",<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cao |first1=Lan |last2=Novas |first2=Himilce |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L1tskNgsz3wC&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=gook |title=Everything You Need to Know About Asian-American History |publisher=[[Plume (publisher)|Plume]] |date=1996 |page=250 |quote=Gook, the American racial epithet for all Asian Americans, is actually the Korean word for 'country.}}</ref> "한국" (''hanguk''), meaning "Korea", or "미국" (''miguk''), meaning "America".<ref>{{cite book |last=Lee |first=Robert G. |title=Orientals: Asian Americans in Popular Culture |publisher=[[Temple University Press]] |date=1999 |quote=A bastardization of the Korean "Hanguk" (Korean), or Miguk (American)"}}</ref> For example, U.S. soldiers might have heard locals saying ''miguk,'' referring to Americans, and misinterpreted this as "Me gook."<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xcf_4T-nPuoC&pg=PA118#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Trans-Pacific Relations: America, Europe, and Asia in the Twentieth Century |publisher=[[Praeger Publishers|Praeger]] |page=117 |date=2003}}</ref> "Mỹ Quốc"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mỹ Quốc in English|url=https://en.glosbe.com/vi/en/M%E1%BB%B9%20Qu%E1%BB%91c|website=Glosbe|accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> is an archaism in [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] that died out due to a [[History of writing in Vietnam|language shift]], starting from just before the [[Indochina Wars]] and culminating with the end of that period often referred to as the [[Vietnam War]], which has the same root and similar pronunciation to Korean "미국" (''miguk'') both stemming from [[Chinese characters]] "美國"(''Měiguó'') also meaning "America."
[[H. L. Mencken|Mencken]] reported the earliest use of the word ''gook'': he wrote that [[United States occupation of Nicaragua|U.S. Marines occupying Nicaragua]] in 1912 took to calling the natives ''gooks'' and that it had previously been a term for Filipinos.<ref name=warslang>{{cite book |last=Dickson |first=Paul |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XGNMBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PR10&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=War Slang |publisher=[[Dover Publications]] |year=2011 |page=29 |quote=Dickson cites Mencken's ''The American Language,'' Supplement 1 (1945)}}</ref> He further mentions that the natives of [[Costa Rica]] are sometimes called ''goo-goos''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mencken |first=H. L. |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=eCNeVLvgCceN7AaLnIGYDg&id=F47NsbOetD0C&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=gooks |title=The American Language |page=296}}</ref> The first written use was in 1920 and mentions that the Marines [[American occupation of Haiti|occupying Haiti]] used the term to refer to [[Haitians]].<ref name=natgoo>{{cite journal |url=http://www.thirdworldtraveler.com/Independent_Media/Conquest_Haiti_SNM.html |title=The Conquest of Haiti |work=[[The Nation]] |date= 10 July 1920}}</ref> U.S. occupation troops in [[South Korea]] after World War II called the [[Koreans]] "gooks".<ref name=pearson>{{cite web|url=http://kpearson.faculty.tcnj.edu/Dictionary/gook.htm |title=Gook |work=Rhetoric of Race |date=2003 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224090837/http://kpearson.faculty.tcnj.edu/Dictionary/gook.htm |archivedate=February 24, 2009 }}</ref><!--Note: Poor reference as [[WP:SPS]]; fails for "me gook"; but good enough for reference to reliable source, namely NY Herald Tribune 2 April 1947 article "Search for a Middle Road in Korea"--> After the return of U.S. troops to the [[Korean Peninsula]], so prevalent was the use of the word gook during the first months of the Korean War that U.S. General [[Douglas MacArthur]] banned its use, for fear that Asians would become alienated to the [[United Nations Command]] because of the insult.<ref name=roegook /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/doc/166121693.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+6%2C+1950&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+%281923-Current+File%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=SOLDIERS+REVIVE+%27GOOK%27+AS+NAME+FOR+KOREA+REDS |title=Soldiers revive "gook" as name for Korea reds |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=6 August 1950 |page=6 }}</ref><ref name=kanmac>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/56230634/ |title=Use of Word "Gook" Is Opposed by MacArthur |work=[[The Kansas City Star]] |date=12 September 1950}}</ref> The term was even used in British Army dispatches during the Korean War; the posthumous [[Victoria Cross]] citation for [[Kenneth Muir (VC)|Major Kenneth Muir]], for the [[Battle of Hill 282]], stated that his last words were: "The Gooks will never drive the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders|Argylls]] off this hill".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39115 |date=5 January 1951 |pages=133–134 |supp=y}}</ref> Although mainly used to describe non-European foreigners, especially East and Southeast Asians, it has been used to describe foreigners in general,<ref name=Flexner>{{cite book |last1=Wentworth |first1=Harold |last2=Flexner |first2=Stuart Berg |title=Dictionary of American Slang |publisher=[[Thomas Y. Crowell Co.]] |date=1960 |quote=''gook'': Generically, a native of the Pacific islands, Africa, Japan, China, Korea or any European country except England; usually a brown-skinned or Oriental non-Christian.}}</ref> including [[Italians]] in 1944, [[Indian people|Indians]], [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] and [[Turkish people|Turks]] in the '70s, and [[Arabs]] in 1988.<ref name=enswear /> This dual usage is similar to the offensive word [[wog]] in [[British English]].
In modern U.S. usage, "gook" refers particularly to [[Communism|communist]] soldiers during the Vietnam War and has also been used towards all Vietnamese and at other times to all East Asians in general. It is considered to be highly offensive. In a highly publicized incident, Senator [[John McCain]] used the word during the [[John McCain presidential campaign, 2000|2000 presidential campaign]] to refer to his former captors: "I hate the gooks. I will hate them as long as I live… I was referring to my [[prison guard]]s and I will continue to refer to them in language that might offend." He later apologized to the Vietnamese community at large.<ref name=awapol>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianweek.com/2000_02_24/feature_mccainapology.html |title=McCain Apologizes for 'Gook' Comment |work=[[Asiaweek]] |date=24 February 2000 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001102101856/http://www.asianweek.com/2000_02_24/feature_mccainapology.html |archivedate=November 2, 2000 }}</ref>
The term has been used by non-U.S. militaries, notably the Rhodesian forces during the [[Rhodesian Bush War]], where it was used interchangeably with ''terr'' and ''terrorist'' to describe the guerrillas,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1980/feb/09/zimbabwe.simonhoggart |title=Ironing the lawn in Salisbury, Rhodesia |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 February 1980}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hyslop |first=Angus |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MtJh00OCBA8C&lpg=PA361&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Jaws of the Lion: Rhodesia Before Zimbabwe |publisher=[[Lulu (company)|Lulu.com]] |date=1997}}</ref> and by Australian forces during the Vietnam War.<ref name=enswear />
The 1960 single "Yogi" by [[The Ivy Three]] contains ''gook'' in the lyrics to describe an Indian [[Yogi]]. The harmless usage of the term in the lyrics indicates that it had become a playful word used to describe certain Asian ethnic groups before its usage Vietnam War redefined the term as an offensive racial epithet.
