{{about|the Turkic tribe|the Russian weapon|Pecheneg machine gun}}
{{Infobox Former Country |common_name = Pecheneg Khanates |native_name = |conventional_long_name = Pecheneg Khanates |continent = Europe |region = |status = [[Khanate]] |capital = |common_languages = [[Pecheneg language|Pecheneg]] |year_start = 860 |year_end = 1091 |p1 = Khazar Khaganate |flag_p1 = |s1 = Kipchaks |s2 = |image_map = Khazarfall1.png |image_map_caption = Pecheneg Khanates and neighboring territories, c.1015 |image_flag = |religion = |currency = |legislature = |title_leader = |leader1 = |year_leader1 = |leader2 = |year_leader2 = |stat_year1 = |stat_area1 = }} {{History of the Turks pre-14th century}}
The '''Pechenegs''' or '''Patzinaks'''<ref>{{lang-tr|Peçenek(ler)}}, {{lang-ro|Pecenegi}}, {{lang-ru|Печенег(и)}}, {{lang-uk|Печеніг(и)}}, {{lang-hu|Besenyő(k)}}, {{lang-hr|Pečenezi}}, {{lang-gr|Πατζινάκοι, Πετσενέγοι, Πατζινακίται}}, {{lang-ka|პაჭანიკი}}, {{lang-bg|печенеги}}, ''pechenegi'' or печенези, ''pechenezi''; {{lang-sr|Печенези}}, {{lang-la|Pacinacae, Bisseni}}</ref> were a [[nomad|semi-nomadic]] [[Turkic peoples|Turkic people]] from [[Central Asia]] speaking the [[Pecheneg language]] which belonged to the [[Oghuz languages|Oghuz]] branch of [[Turkic languages|Turkic language family]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Akdes|first1=Nimet Kurat|title=Peçenek Tarihi|date=1937|pages=22–26|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref> Three of the ruling clans of the Pechenegs were the [[Kankalis]]/Kangli.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
== Ethnonym ==
The Pechenegs were mentioned as ''Bjnak'', ''Bjanak'' or ''Bajanak'' in medieval [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] texts, as ''Be-ča-nag'' in [[Classical Tibetan]] documents, as ''Pačanak-i'' in works written in [[Georgian language|Georgian]], and as ''Pacinnak'' in [[Armenian language|Armenian]].{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=93}} [[Anna Komnene]] and other Byzantine authors referred to them as ''Patzinakoi'' or ''Patzinakitai''.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=93}} In [[medieval Latin]] texts, the Pechenegs were referred to as ''Pizenaci'', ''Bisseni'' or ''Bessi''.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=93}} [[East Slavic peoples]] use the terms ''Pečenegi'' or ''Pečenezi'', while the [[Poles]] mention them as ''Pieczyngowie'' or ''Piecinigi''.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=93}} The Hungarian word for Pecheneg is ''besenyő''; the Romanian term is "Pecenegi"{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=93}} The [[ethnonym]] derived from the [[Old Turkic language|Old Turkic]] word for "brother-in-law” (''baja'', ''baja-naq'' or ''bajinaq''), implying that it initially referred to an "in-law related clan or tribe".{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=93}}{{sfn|Golden|2003|p=I.64}}
Three of the eight Pecheneg "provinces" or clans were collectively known as Kangars.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=182}} According to [[Constantine VII Porphyrogenitus]], the Kangars received this denomination because "they are more valiant and noble than the rest" of the people "and that is what the title Kangar signifies".{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=182}}<ref>''Constantine Porphyrogenitus: De Administrando Imperio'' (ch. 37), p. 171.</ref> For no Turkic word with similar meaning is known, [[Ármin Vámbéry]] connected the ethnonym to the [[Kirghiz language|Kirghiz]] words ''kangir'' ("agile"), ''kangirmak'' ("to go out riding") and ''kani-kara'' ("black-blooded"), while [[Carlile Aylmer Macartney]] associated it with the [[Chagatai language|Chagatai]] word ''gang'' ("chariot").{{sfn|Macartney|1968|pp=104-105}} [[Omeljan Pritsak]] proposed that the name had initially been a composite term ''(Kängär As)'' deriving from the [[Tocharian languages|Tocharian]] word for stone ''(kank)'' and the [[Iranian languages|Iranian]] ethnonym ''As''.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=213}} If the latter assumption is valid, the Kangars' ethnonym suggests that Iranian elements contributed to the formation of the Pecheneg people.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=94}}
== Language == {{Main|Pecheneg language}} [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]], an 11th-century man of letters specialized in Turkic dialects argued that the language spoken by the Pechenegs was a variant of the [[Cuman language|Cuman]] and [[Oghuz languages|Oghuz]] idioms.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=95}} He suggested that foreign influences on the Pechenegs gave rise to phonetical differences between their tongue and the idiom spoken by other Turkic peoples.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=181}} Anna Komnene likewise stated that the Pechenegs and the Cumans shared a common language.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=95}} Although the Pecheneg language itself died out centuries ago,{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=343}} the names of the Pecheneg "provinces" recorded by Constantine Porphyrogenitus prove that the Pechenegs spoke a Turkic language.{{sfn|Róna-Tas|1999|p=239}} The [[Huns]], [[Khazars]] and Pechenegs are thought to have belonged to the same [[proto-Turkic]] group of languages as the modern [[Chuvash language]] ([[Oghur languages|Oghur]] dialects).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&id=9udBAAAAYAAJ Ukraine: a concise encyclopaedia, Volume 1], pg. 929. Published for the Ukrainian National Association, University of Toronto Press 1963.</ref>
== History ==
=== Origins ===
[[Paul Pelliot]] originated the proposal that the ''[[Book of Sui]]''{{mdash}}a 7th-century Chinese work{{mdash}}preserved the earliest record on the Pechenegs.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=211}} The book mentioned the ''Pei-ju'' people who had settled near the ''En-ch'u'' and ''A-lan'' peoples (identified as [[Onogurs]] and [[Alans]], respectively), to the east of ''Fu-lin'' (or the [[Eastern Roman Empire]]).{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=211}}{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}} [[Victor Spinei]] emphasizes that the Pechenegs' association with the ''Pei-ju'' is "uncertain".{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}} He proposes that a 8th-century Uighur envoy's report, which survives in Tibetan translation,{{sfn|Róna-Tas|1999|p=235}} contains the first certain reference to the Pechenegs.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}} The report recorded an armed conflict between the ''Be-ča-nag'' and the ''[[Uar|Hor]]'' (or [[Ouzes|Ouze]]) peoples in the region of the river [[Syr Darya]].{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}}
[[Ibn Khordadbeh]] (c. 820 – 912 CE), [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]] (11th century), [[Muhammad al-Idrisi]] (1100–1165), and many other [[Muslim]] scholars agree that the Pechenegs belonged to the Turkic peoples.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=182}} The ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]'' stated that the "Torkmens, Pechenegs, [[Torks]], and [[Polovci]]ans" descended from "the godless sons of [[Ishmael]], who had been sent as a chastisement to the Christians".{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=186}}<ref>''Russian Primary Chronicle'' (year 6604/1096), p. 184)</ref> [[Omeljan Pritsak]] says that the Pechenegs' homeland was located between the [[Aral Sea]] and the middle course of the Syr Darya, along the important trade routes connecting Central Asia with Eastern Europe.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|pp=211-212}} The [[Orkhon inscriptions]] listed the Kangars among the subject peoples of the [[Eastern Turkic Khaganate]].{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=211}}
=== Westward migration ===
The [[Turkic Khaganate]] collapsed in 744 which gave rise to a series of inter-tribal confrontations in the [[Eurasian steppes]].{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=212}} The [[Karluks]] attacked the [[Oghuz Turks]], forcing them to launch a westward migration towards the Pechenegs' lands.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=212}} The Uighur envoy's report testifies that the Oghuz and Pecheneg waged war against each other already in the 8th century, most probably for the control of the trade routes.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=212}} The Oghuz made an alliance with the Karluks and [[Kimaks]] and defeated the Pechenegs and their allies in a battle near the Lake Aral before 850, according to the 10th-century scholar, [[Al-Masudi]].{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=212}} Most Pechenegs launched a new migration towards the [[Volga River]], but some groups were forced to join the Oghuz.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=212}} The latter formed the 19th tribe of the Oghuz tribal federation in the 11th century.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|pp=212}}{{sfn|Golden|2003|p=I.64}}
The Pechenegs who leaved their homeland settled between the [[Ural River|Ural]] and Volga rivers.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=213}} Their new territory was quite large, with a 30-day-walk extension, according to Muslim sources.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=213}}{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=114}} Their territory bordered on the [[Khazars]], Slavs, [[Cumans]] and Ouzes.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=114}} The Pechenegs made regular raids against their neighbors and sold their captives.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=114}} The Khazars made an alliance with the Ouzes against the Pechenegs and they invaded the Pechenegs' land from two directions.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|pp=213}} The double attack forced the Pechenegs into a new westward migration.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|pp=213}} They marched across the Khazar Khaganate and expelled the Magyars from the lands along the [[Kuban River]] and the upper course of the river [[Donets]].{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|pp=213}} The ''[[Hudud al-'Alam]]''{{mdash}}a late 10th-century Persian geography{{mdash}}distinguished two Pecheneg groups, referreing to those who lived along the Donets as "Turkic Pechenegs", and to those along the Kuban as "Khazarian Pechenegs".{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|pp=213}} The latter denominations implies that some Pecheneg tribes had been forced to acknowledge the Khazars supremacy.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}}
According to [[Gardizi]] and other Muslim scholars who based their works on 9th-century sources, the Pechenegs' new territories were bordered by the [[Cumans]], [[Khazars]], Oghuz Turks and [[Slavic peoples|Slavs]].{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=114}}{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}} The same sources also narrate that the Pechenegs regularly waged war against the Khazars and the latter's vassals, the [[Burtas]].{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}}{{sfn|Spinei|2003|pp=113-114}} The Khazars and the Oghuz Turks made an alliance against the Pechenegs and attacked them.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}}{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=138}}{{Citation not found}} Outnumbered by the enemy, the Pechenegs started a new migration, invaded the dwelling places of the [[Hungarians]] and forced them to leave.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=138}}{{Citation not found}}{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}} There is no consensual date for this second migration of the Pechenegs: Pritsak argues that it took place around 830,{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}} but Kristó suggests that it could hardly occur before the 850s.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=144}}{{Citation not found}} The Pechenegs settled along the rivers [[Seversky Donets River|Donets]] and [[Kuban River|Kuban]].{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}}
It is plausible that the distinction between the "Turkic Pechenegs" and "Khazar Pechenegs" mentioned in the 10th-century ''[[Hudud al-'alam]]'' had its origin in this period.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}} Spinei proposes that the latter denomination most probably refers to Pecheneg groups accepting Khazar suzerainty.{{sfn|Spinei|2003|p=113}} In addition to these two branches, a third group of Pechenegs existed in this period: Constantine Porphyrogenitus and [[Ibn Fadlan]] mention that those who decided not to leave their homeland were incorporated into the Oghuz federation of Turkic tribes.{{sfn|Golden|2003|p=I.64}}{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}} However, it is uncertain whether this groups' formation is connected to the Pechenegs' first or second migration (as it is proposed by Pritsak and Golden, respectively).{{sfn|Golden|2003|p=I.64}}{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}} According to Mahmud al-Kashgari, one of the ''[[Oghuz Turks#Traditional tribal organization|Üçok]]'' clans of the Oghuz Turks{{sfn|Atalay|2006|p=I.57}} was still formed by Pechenegs in the 1060s.{{sfn|Pritsak|1975|p=214}}
{{Quote|Originally, the Pechenegs had their dwelling on the river Atil (Volga), and likewise on the river Geïch, having common frontiers with the Chazars and the so-called Uzes. But fifty years ago the so-called Uzes made common cause with the Chazars and joined battle with the Pechenegs and prevailed over them and expelled them from their country, which the so-called Uzes have occupied till this day. [...] At the time when the Pechenegs were expelled from their country, some of them of their own will and personal decision stayed behind there and united with the so-called Uzes, and even to this day they live among them, and wear such distinguishing marks as separate them off and betray their origin and how it came about that they were split off from their own folk: for their tunics are short, reaching to the knee, and their sleeves are cut off at the shoulder, whereby, you see, they indicate that they have been cut off from their own folk and those of their race.|[[Constantine Porphyrogenitus]]: ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]''<ref>''Constantine Porphyrogenitus: De Administrando Imperio'' (ch. 37), pp. 167., 169.</ref>}}
== Origins and area == In [[Mahmud Kashgari]]'s 11th-century work ''Dīwān lughāt al-turk'' ({{lang-ar|ديوان لغات الترك}}),<ref>{{Cite book | publisher = Tekin | last = Maḥmūd | first = Kāshgarī |author2=James Kelly | title = Türk Şiveleri Lügatı = Dīvānü Luġāt-It-Türk | location = Duxbury, Mass | year = 1982 }}</ref> the name ''Beçenek'' is given two meanings. The first is "a Turkish nation living around the country of [[Rome|the Rum]]", where ''Rum'' was the Turkish word for the [[Eastern Roman Empire]] (Byzantine Empire). Kashgari's second definition of ''Beçenek'' is "a branch of [[Oghuz Turks]]"; he subsequently described the Oghuz as being formed of 22 branches, of which the 19th branch was named ''Beçenek''. [[Max Vasmer]] derives this name from the Turkic word for "brother-in-law, relative" ({{lang-tk|bacanak}} and {{lang-tr|bacanak}}).
By the 9th and 10th centuries, they controlled much of the steppes of southeast [[Europe]] and the [[Crimean Peninsula]]. Although an important factor in the region at the time, like most nomadic tribes their concept of statecraft failed to go beyond random attacks on neighbours and spells as mercenaries for other powers.
According to [[Constantine VII|Constantine Porphyrogenitus]], writing in c. 950, Patzinakia, the Pecheneg realm, stretched west as far as the [[Siret River]] (or even the Eastern [[Carpathian Mountains]]), and was four days distant from "Tourkias" (i.e. [[Hungary]]).{{Quote|The whole of Patzinakia is divided into eight provinces with the same number of great princes. The provinces are these: the name of the first province is Irtim; of the second, Tzour; of the third, Gyla; of the fourth, Koulpeï; of the fifth, Charaboï; of the sixth, Talmat; of the seventh, Chopon; of the eighth, Tzopon. At the time at which the Pechenegs were expelled from their country, their princes were, in the province of Irtim, Baïtzas; in Tzour, Kouel; in Gyla, Kourkoutai; in Koulpeï, Ipaos; in Charaboï, Kaïdoum; in the province of Talmat, Kostas; in Chopon, Giazis; in the province of Tzopon, Batas.|[[Constantine VII|Constantine Porphyrogenitus]]: ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]''<ref>''Constantine Porphyrogenitus: De Administrando Imperio'' (ch. 37), p. 167.</ref>}}
According to [[Omeljan Pritsak]], the Pechenegs are descendants from the ancient [[Kangly|Kangars]] who originate from [[Tashkent]].
== In Armenian sources ==
In the Armenian chronicles of [[Matthew of Edessa]] Pechenegs are mentioned a couple of times. The first mention is in chapter 75, where it says that in the year 499 (according to the old Armenian calendar — years 1050–51 according to the [[Gregorian calendar]]) the ''Badzinag'' nation caused great destruction in many provinces of Rome, i.e. the [[Byzantine]] territories. The second is in chapter 103, which is about the [[Battle of Manzikert]]. In that chapter it is told that the allies of Rome, ''Padzunak'' and ''Uz'' (some branches of the [[Oghuz Turks]]) tribes which changed their sides at the peak of the battle and began fighting against the [[Byzantine]] forces, side by side with the [[Seljuq Turks]]. In the 132nd chapter a war between Rome and the ''Padzinags'' is described and after the defeat of the Roman (Byzantine) Army, an unsuccessful siege of [[Constantinople]] by the ''Padzinags'' is mentioned. In that chapter, the ''Patzinags'' are described as an "all archer army". In chapter 299, the Armenian prince, ''Vasil'', who was in the Roman Army, sent a platoon of ''Padzinags'' (they had settled in the city of Misis, around modern [[Adana]], which is far away from the lands where Pechenegs were then mainly living) to the aid of the Christians.<!--sorry, I can't parse this; we need a critical evaluation: may Matthew's evidence be trusted? -->
== Alliance with Byzantium == [[File:63-manasses-chronicle.jpg|thumb|Sviatoslav enters Bulgaria with Pecheneg allies,<ref>[[Tania Velmans]] Three Notes On Miniatures In The Chronicle of Manasses Macedonian Studies https://archive.org/details/ProblemsOfByzantineHistoriographyThreeNotesOnMiniaturesInThe</ref> from the Constantine Manasses Chronicle.]]
In the 9th century, the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] became allied with the Pechenegs, using them to fend off other, more dangerous tribes such as [[Kievan Rus']] and the [[Magyars]].
The Uzes, another [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] steppe people, eventually expelled the Pechenegs from their homeland; in the process, they also seized most of their livestock and other goods. An alliance of [[Oghuz Turks|Oghuz]], [[Kimeks]], and [[Karluks]] was also pressing the Pechenegs, but another group, the [[Samanid]]s, defeated that alliance. Driven further west by the [[Khazars]] and [[Cuman people|Cumans]] by 889, the Pechenegs in turn drove the Magyars west of the [[Dnieper]] River by 892.
[[Bulgarians|Bulgarian]] [[Tsar Simeon I]] employed the Pechenegs to help fend off the Magyars. The Pechenegs were so successful that they drove out the Magyars remaining in [[Etelköz]] and the [[Pontic steppes]], forcing them westward towards the [[Pannonian plain]], where they later founded the [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian state]].
== Late history and decline ==
In the 9th century the Pechenegs began a period of wars against [[Kievan Rus']]. For more than two centuries they had launched raids into the lands of Rus', which sometimes escalated into full-scale wars (like the 920 war on the Pechenegs by [[Igor of Kiev]], reported in the ''[[Primary Chronicle]]''). The Pecheneg wars against Kievan Rus' caused the Slavs from Walachian territories to gradually migrate north of the Dniestr in the 10th and 11th centuries.<ref>V. Klyuchevsky, The course of the Russian history. v.1: "Myslʹ.1987, {{ISBN|5-244-00072-1}}</ref> Rus'/Pecheneg temporary military alliances also occurred however, as during the Byzantine campaign in 943 led by Igor.<ref>[[Ibn Haukal]] describes the Pechenegs as the long-standing allies of the Rus', whom they invariably accompanied during the 10th century [[Caspian expeditions of the Rus|Caspian expeditions]].</ref> In 968 the Pechenegs [[Siege of Kiev (968)|attacked and besieged Kiev]]; some joined the Prince of Kiev, [[Sviatoslav I, Prince of Kiev|Sviatoslav I]], in his Byzantine campaign of 970–971, though eventually they ambushed and killed the Kievan prince in 972. According to the ''Primary Chronicle'', the Pecheneg [[Khan (title)|Khan]] [[Kurya (khan)|Kurya]] made a [[Chalice (cup)|chalice]] from Sviatoslav's skull, in accordance with the custom of [[steppe]] nomads. The fortunes of the Rus'-Pecheneg confrontation swung during the reign of [[Vladimir I of Kiev]] (990–995), who founded the town of [[Pereyaslav]] upon the site of his victory over the Pechenegs,<ref>The chronicler explains the town's name, derived from the Slavic word for "retake", by the fact that Vladimir "retook" the military glory from the Pechenegs.</ref> followed by the defeat of the Pechenegs during the reign of [[Yaroslav I the Wise]] in 1036. Shortly thereafter, other nomadic peoples replaced the weakened Pechenegs in the [[Pontic steppe]]: the [[Cuman people|Cumans]] and the [[Torks]]. According to [[Mykhailo Hrushevsky]] (''History of Ukraine-Ruthenia''), after its defeat near Kiev the Pecheneg Horde moved towards the [[Danube]], crossed the river, and disappeared out of the [[Pontic steppes]]. [[File:MadridSkylitzesFol173ra.jpg|thumb|left|300px|The Pechenegs slaughter the "skyths" of [[Sviatoslav I of Kiev]].]]
After centuries of fighting involving all their neighbours—the Byzantine Empire, [[Bulgaria]], Kievan Rus', Khazaria, and the Magyars—the Pechenegs were annihilated as an independent force in 1091 at the [[Battle of Levounion]] by a combined Byzantine and Cuman army under Byzantine Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]]. Alexios I recruited the defeated Pechenegs, whom he settled in the district of [[Moglena]] (today in [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]]) into a [[Tagma (military)|tagma]] "of the Moglena Pechenegs".<ref>Haldon, John, ''Warfare, State And Society In The Byzantine World 560-1204'', Routledge, 2002, p. 117.</ref> Attacked again in 1094 by the Cumans, many Pechenegs were slain or absorbed. The Byzantines defeated the Pechenegs again at the [[Battle of Beroia]] in 1122, on the territory of modern-day Bulgaria. For some time, significant communities of Pechenegs still remained in the Kingdom of Hungary. With time the Balkan Pechenegs lost their national identity and became fully assimilated, mostly with [[Magyars]] and [[Bulgarians]].
In the 12th century, according to Byzantine historian [[John Kinnamos]], the Pechenegs fought as [[mercenaries]] for the [[List of Byzantine emperors|Byzantine Emperor]] [[Manuel I Komnenos]] in [[Catepanate of Italy|southern Italy]] against the [[Normans|Norman]] [[king of Sicily]], [[William I of Sicily|William the Bad]].<ref>Kinnamos, IV, 4, p. 143</ref> A group of Pechenegs was present at the battle of [[Andria, Italy|Andria]] in 1155.<ref>[[Ferdinand Chalandon|Chalandon]] (1907)</ref>
The Pechenegs were last mentioned in 1168 as members of Turkic tribes known in the chronicles as the "[[Chorni Klobuky]] (Black Hats)".<ref>Ivan Katchanovski, Zenon E. Kohut, Bohdan Y. Nebesio, Myroslav Yurkevich, ''Historical Dictionary of Ukraine'', Scarecrow Press, 2013, p. 439.</ref>
In 15th-century Hungary, some people adopted the surname ''Besenyö'' ([[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] for "Pecheneg"); they were most numerous in the [[county of Tolna]]. One of the earliest introductions of [[Islam]] into [[Eastern Europe]] came about through the work of an early 11th-century Muslim prisoner who was captured by the Byzantines. The Muslim prisoner was brought into the [[Bosnia (region)|Besenyö]] territory of the Pechenegs, where he taught and converted individuals to Islam.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=O45CAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=thomas+walker+arnold+preaching&hl=en&ei=Vh74TLilEIOdlgfN34ifAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false The preaching of Islam: a history of the propagation of the Muslim faith By Sir Thomas Walker Arnold, pg. 335]</ref> In the late 12th century, [[Abu Hamid al Garnathi]] referred to Hungarian Pechenegs – probably Muslims – living disguised as Christians. In the southeast of Serbia, there is a village called Pecenjevce founded by Pechenegs. After war with Byzantium, the broken remnants of the tribes found refuge in the area, where they established their settlement.
