This is a '''timeline of women rabbis in the United States'''.
* 1972: [[Sally Priesand]] became the first female rabbi ordained in the U.S., and is believed to be only the second woman ever to be formally ordained in the history of Judaism.<ref name=NYT1972>Blau, Eleanor. [https://www.nytimes.com/1972/06/04/archives/1st-woman-rabbi-in-us-ordained-she-may-be-only-the-second-in.html "1st Woman Rabbi in U.S. Ordained; She May Be Only the Second in History of Judaism"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 4, 1972. Retrieved September 17, 2009. "Sally J. Priesand was ordained at the Isaac M. Wise Temple here today, becoming the first woman rabbi in this country and it is believed, the second in the history of Judaism."</ref> * 1974: [[Sandy Eisenberg Sasso]] became the first female rabbi in [[Reconstructionist Judaism]].<ref> {{cite book |page=475 |title=Encyclopedia of gender and society, Volume 1 |first1=Jodi A.|last1=O'Brien |first2=Jodi|last2=O'Brien |editor-first=Jodi A.|editor-last=O'Brien |publisher=SAGE |year=2009 |isbn=978-1-4129-0916-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_nyHS4WyUKEC&dq=sally+sasso+reconstructionist&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref><ref name="jwa">{{cite web|url=http://jwa.org/blog/sandy-eisenberg-sasso|title=Celebrating Sandy Eisenberg Sasso, the first woman Reconstructionalist rabbi|publisher=jwa.org |date=May 19, 2010 |accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref> * 1975: The [[Women's Rabbinic Network]], an American national organization for female Reform rabbis, was founded in 1975 by female rabbinic students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/rabbis-in-united-states |title=Rabbis in the United States &#124; Jewish Women's Archive |publisher=Jwa.org |date=1903-02-14 |accessdate=2013-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adatelohim.org/Rabbi-Rebecca-Dubowe-s/7183.htm |title=Rabbi Rebecca Dubowe - Temple Adat Elohim |publisher=Adatelohim.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://womensrabbinicnetwork.org/ |title=Home |publisher=Womensrabbinicnetwork.org |date=2017-08-24 |accessdate=2017-09-26}}</ref> * 1976: [[Michal Mendelsohn]] became the first presiding female rabbi in a North American congregation when she was hired by Temple Beth El Shalom in San Jose, California.<ref name="jta">{{cite web|url=http://archive.jta.org/article/1979/08/23/2985422/22-women-now-ordained-as-rabbis-most-of-them-do-not-have-pulpits|title=22 Women Now Ordained As Rabbis Most of Them Do Not Have Pulpits|publisher=archive.jta.org|date=August 23, 1979|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name="jweekly">{{cite web|url=http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/67760/the-little-shul-that-could-with-just-seven-members-san-jose-congregation-ke/|title=The little shul that could: With just seven members, San Jose congregation keeps chugging along|publisher=www.jweekly.com|date=February 14, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref> * 1977: [[Sandy Eisenberg Sasso]] and her husband Dennis Sasso became the first couple to serve jointly as rabbis when they were hired by Beth-El Zedeck in Indianapolis.<ref name="indystar">{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20130519/LIFE/130519002/-Trail-blazing-Rabbi-Sandy-Sasso-retiring-after-36-years|title=Trail-blazing Rabbi Sandy Sasso retiring after 36 years|publisher=www.indystar.com|date=May 19, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref> * 1979: [[Linda Joy Holtzman]] became the first woman to serve as a rabbi for a Conservative congregation when she was hired by [[Beth Israel Congregation of Chester County]], which was then located in Coatesville, Pennsylvania.<ref name="jta" /> She had graduated in 1979 from the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]] in Philadelphia, yet was hired by Beth Israel despite their being a Conservative congregation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1346&dat=19790818&id=xLMwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-PoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5186,1102901|title=First woman rabbi to head temple seeks to lead way for more women|author=''[[The New York Times]]''|publisher=''[[The Ledger]]''|date=August 18, 1979|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> * 1981: [[Helene Ferris]] became the first second-career female rabbi.<ref name=ferris>{{cite news|last=Schwartz|first=Penny|title=In their 40s and 50s, embarking on second careers as rabbis|url=http://www.jta.org/2011/07/28/life-religion/in-their-40s-and-50s-embarking-on-second-careers-as-rabbis|accessdate=August 2, 2013|newspaper=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]|date=July 28, 2011}}</ref><ref name=priv>{{cite news|last=Shaw|first=Dan|title=He Got His Workshop, She Got Her Privacy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/03/realestate/03habi.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=September 4, 2012 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 3, 2008}}</ref><ref name="swfs2">{{cite web |url=http://www.swfs.org/4-decades-women-rabbis/ |title=Stephen Wise Synagogue > 4 Decades of Women Rabbis In the Rabbinate and SWFS |publisher=Swfs.org |date= |accessdate=September 3, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525181437/http://www.swfs.org/4-decades-women-rabbis/ |archivedate=May 25, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> * 1981: [[Lynn Gottlieb]] became the first female rabbi in Jewish Renewal.<ref name="gottlieb">{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/library/br150.htm |title=Pioneering rabbi finds deep satisfaction in storytelling, living life...|publisher=www.fau.edu/library/br150.htm |date=January 2, 2000 |accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref> * 1981: [[Bonnie Koppell]] became the first female rabbi to serve in the U.S. military.<ref name="jewishvirtuallibrary1981">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/bonniekappell.html |title=Bonnie Koppell |publisher=Jewishvirtuallibrary.org |date=May 26, 1981 |accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref><ref name="azrabbi1">{{cite web|url=http://www.azrabbi.com/aboutme.html|title=Rabbi Bonnie Koppell: About Me|publisher=www.azrabbi.com|accessdate=August 31, 2013}}</ref> She joined the army reserves in 1978 while a rabbinical student at the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical College]] in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania,<ref name="jewishvirtuallibrary1981"/><ref name="azrabbi1"/> and was ordained in 1981.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KSEkyUZOxG0C&pg=PA195&lpg=PA195&dq=%22bonnie+koppell%22+ordained+1981&source=bl&ots=oekA07x_Ql&sig=9BQGr5TsAwLL3-HWtvQBb4ttRj8&hl=en&ei=eXKIToueF4Tm0QHmtpXxDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22bonnie%20koppell%22%20ordained%201981&f=false |title=Yiddishe Mamas: The Truth About the Jewish Mother, by Marnie Winston-Macauley - Google Books, pg. 195|date=2007|publisher=Books.google.com |accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref> * 1985: [[Amy Eilberg]] became the first female rabbi in Conservative Judaism.<ref name="amyeilberg">{{cite web|url=http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/eilberg-amy |title=Amy Eilberg|publisher=jwa.org/|accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref> * 1986: [[Amy Perlin]] became the first female rabbi in America to start her own congregation, Temple B'nai Shalom in [[Fairfax Station]], which she was the founding rabbi of in 1986.<ref name="tbs-online1">{{cite web|url=http://www.tbs-online.org/pages/about-us/clergy/meet-our-rabbis/ |title=Temple B'nai Shalom - Northern VA Reform Synagogue - Clergy |publisher=Tbs-online.org |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name="washingtonjewishweek1">{{cite web |url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/main.asp?SectionID=4&SubSectionID=4&ArticleID=18441 |title=Building a community of women - Washington Jewish Week - Online Edition - Rockville, MD |publisher=Washington Jewish Week |date=November 28, 2012 |accessdate=April 20, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226133810/http://washingtonjewishweek.com/main.asp?SectionID=4&SubSectionID=4&ArticleID=18441 |archivedate=December 26, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> * 1986: [[Rabbi Leslie Alexander|Leslie Alexander]] became the first female rabbi of a major Conservative Jewish synagogue in the United States in 1986 at Adat Ari El synagogue in North Hollywood.<ref name="women rabbis">{{cite web|title=Rabbi Reaches Her Pulpit at End of a Long, Circuitous Path|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-11-20/news/vw-11980_1_women-rabbis|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 5, 2013|author=Idelle Davidson|date=November 20, 1986}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=JUDITH CUMMINGS, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/08/03/us/milestone-for-conservative-judaism.html |title=Milestone For Conservative Judaism |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=August 3, 1986 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1986/First-Woman-Rabbi-of-Major-Conservative-Synagogue-Leads-Services/id-cb1bc94ed222af2fe0a9f0a2eac4aed3 |title=First Woman Rabbi of Major Conservative Synagogue Leads Services |publisher=Apnewsarchive.com |date=August 2, 1986 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref> * 1986: [[Julie Schwartz (rabbi)|Julie Schwartz]] became the first woman to serve as an active-duty Jewish chaplain in the U.S. Navy.<ref name="thecitizen">{{cite web |author1=Lance Cummins - Instant Impact Designs - webmaster@thecitizennews.com |url=http://www.thecitizen.com/archive/main/archive-990912/fp-01.html |title=South side's first Jewish congregation ready to move forward |publisher=Thecitizen.com |date=July 9, 1999 |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019070448/http://www.thecitizen.com/archive/main/archive-990912/fp-01.html |archivedate=October 19, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="thecitizen" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Goldman |first=Ari L. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/06/18/us/issue-of-women-as-rabbis-breaks-up-jewish-unit.html |title=Issue Of Women As Rabbis Breaks Up Jewish Unit |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=June 18, 1986 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref> * 1987: [[Joy Levitt]] became the first female president of the [[Reconstructionist Rabbinical Association]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WPILfbtT5tQC&pg=PA553&lpg=PA553&dq=%22joy+levitt%22+%22reconstructionist+rabbinical+association%22+president&source=bl&ots=3OcLwyqeJL&sig=Y4g1Pd3wbp6x0hDKDf37t_sE2Bc&hl=en&ei=1TrdTu2rK6Ha0QHpz_2UAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22joy%20levitt%22%20%22reconstructionist%20rabbinical%20association%22%20president&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Women and Religion in North America, pg. 553. - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2006 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref> * 1988: [[Stacy Offner]] became the first openly lesbian rabbi hired by a mainstream Jewish congregation (Shir Tikvah in Minneapolis).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.womenspress.com/main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=3074 |title=Rumor has it ... - Minnesota Women's Press - St. Paul, MN |publisher=Womenspress.com |date= |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://urj.org/about/union/pr/2008/rabbi_offner/|title=Rabbi Offner|publisher=urj.org|date=2008|accessdate=September 13, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202124328/http://urj.org/about/union/pr/2008/rabbi_offner/|archivedate=February 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shirtikvah.net/Rabbis |title=Rabbis in Social Action |publisher=Shir Tikvah |date=February 14, 2013 |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013215324/http://www.shirtikvah.net/Rabbis |archivedate=October 13, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>Dana Evan Kaplan [https://books.google.com/books?id=qQoaBa7D-9oC&pg=PA255 Contemporary American Judaism: transformation and renewal] Columbia University Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0231137281}}, p. 255</ref><ref>[http://www.shirtikvah.net/Default.aspx?pageId=675181 Our Roots]. Shir Tikvah. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lilith.org/articles/coming-out-in-jewish-family/|title="Coming Out" in the Jewish Family|publisher=Lilith Magazine|date=Summer 1989|accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref> * 1992: [[Karen Soria]] became the first female rabbi to serve in the U.S. Marines, which she did from 1992 until 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omjs.ca/staffbiographies |title=Staff Biographies |publisher=www.omjs.ca |date= |accessdate=July 21, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004105122/http://www.omjs.ca/staffbiographies |archivedate=October 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="cjnews1">{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15581&Itemid=86 |title=The Canadian Jewish News - Winnipeg rabbi served in the marines, navy |publisher=Cjnews.com |date=October 30, 2008 |accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishtribune.ca/lifestyle/2013/04/16/rabbi-tackles-lgbt-in-jewish-life |title=Rabbi tackles LGBT in Jewish life &#124; Jewish Tribune |publisher=Jewishtribune.ca |date=April 16, 2013 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref> * 1993: [[Rebecca Dubowe]] became the first Deaf woman to be ordained as a rabbi in the United States.<ref name="forward.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.forward.com/articles/129451/ |title=The Sisterhood 50: America's Influential Women Rabbis, dated 2010, published July 21, 2010, issue of July 30, 2010|accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="gallaudet.edu">[http://www.gallaudet.edu/daily_digest/eventxite_-_announcements/wsjd_prepassover_seder.html Galludet University website, "Pre-Passover seder hosted by the Washington Society of Jewish Deaf"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929192847/http://www.gallaudet.edu/daily_digest/eventxite_-_announcements/wsjd_prepassover_seder.html |date=September 29, 2011}}</ref> * 1993: [[Chana Timoner]] became the first female rabbi to hold an active duty assignment as a chaplain in the U.S. Army.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-07-18/news/9807180215_1_fort-bragg-chaplain-fort-benning |title=Chana Timoner – Orlando Sentinel |publisher=Articles.orlandosentinel.com |date=July 18, 1998 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref><ref name="nytimes1998">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/17/nyregion/chana-timoner-46-rabbi-and-chaplain-dies.html |title=Chana Timoner, 46, Rabbi and Chaplain, Dies – New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=July 17, 1998 |accessdate=November 10, 2011}}</ref> * 1994: [[Laura Geller]] became the first woman to lead a major metropolitan congregation, specifically Temple Emanuel in Beverly Hills.<ref name="Tebh.org">{{cite web |url=http://www.tebh.org/about/clergy.php |title=Rabbi Laura Geller &#124; Rabbi Jonathan Aaron &#124; Rabbi Jill Zimmerman &#124; Los Angeles |publisher=Tebh.org |date=August 24, 2006 |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229093127/http://www.tebh.org/about/clergy.php |archivedate=February 29, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/geller-laura |title=Laura Geller &#124; Jewish Women's Archive |publisher=Jwa.org |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> * 1994 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/41443255?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents Rabbi Shohama Wiener] became the first woman to head a Jewish seminary, the [http://www.ajrsem.org Academy for Jewish Religion]. * 1995: [[Dianne Cohler-Esses]] became the first Syrian woman to become a rabbi, and the first Syrian non-Orthodox rabbi, when she was ordained by the [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mishpacha.org/credits.shtml|title=Mispacha: A virtual community for real Jewish families|publisher=www.mishpacha.org|accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Rabbi Dianne Cohler-Esses">{{cite web |url=http://www.mechonhadar.org/c/journal/view_article_content?groupId=10488&articleId=27423&version=1.0 |title=Rabbi Dianne Cohler-Esses |publisher=Mechonhadar.org |accessdate=November 17, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726081552/http://www.mechonhadar.org/c/journal/view_article_content?groupId=10488&articleId=27423&version=1.0 |archivedate=July 26, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="thejewishweek1">{{cite web|author=Dianne Cohler-Esses |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/special_sections/text_context/my_fathers_synagogue |title=Connecting the World to Jewish News, Culture, and Opinion |publisher=The Jewish Week |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref><ref name="Rabbi Dianne Cohler-Esses"/><ref name="romemu1">{{cite web |url=http://romemu.org/hebrew-school/romemu-names-first-syrian-jewish-female-rabbi-to-be-director-of-education |title=Names First Syrian Jewish Female Rabbi to be Director of Education |publisher=Romemu |date=August 8, 2012 |accessdate=November 17, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415174030/http://romemu.org/hebrew-school/romemu-names-first-syrian-jewish-female-rabbi-to-be-director-of-education |archivedate=April 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> * 1996: [[Cynthia Culpeper]] became the first pulpit rabbi to announce being diagnosed with [[AIDS]], which she did when she was rabbi of [[Agudath Israel Etz Ahayem|Agudath Israel]] in [[Montgomery, Alabama]].<ref name="exponent">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.jewishexponent.com/article/960/Cynthia_Culpeper_Dies_Rabbi_Who/ |title=Cynthia Culpeper Dies, Rabbi Who Battled AIDS |publisher=The Jewish Exponent |date=September 15, 2005 |accessdate=October 14, 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> * 1999: [[Tamara Kolton]] became the very first rabbi of either sex in Humanistic Judaism.<ref name="shj">{{cite web |url=http://www.shj.org/shjbios.htm |title=Society for Humanistic Judaism - Rabbis and Leadership |publisher=Shj.org |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928164758/http://www.shj.org/shjbios.htm |archivedate=September 28, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> * 2000: [[Helga Newmark]], born in Germany, became the first female Holocaust survivor ordained as a rabbi. She was ordained in America.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://huc.edu/newspubs/pressroom/article.php?pressroomid=2004 |title=HUC-JIR: Press Room - In Memoriam: Rabbi Helga Newmark, z'&#39;l |publisher=Huc.edu |date=March 8, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:T7pdxC2hw_IJ:english-8.saintcats.org/modules/locker/files/get_group_file.phtml?fid%3D13501479%26gid%3D2555519%26sessionid%3D+helga+newmark+rabbi+born&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjJ1BwH3SzBY_P-UoaDTEgD-CTT4Xu2RHwayY2v99CPI4xNExg23CckBh7bcy8suMpu3AkQEW0GIm5WwU15q9RqLdFOoezZMBx91pF2bpD7DLQxVaTspWJXc-j7RlDVU5iRepDF&sig=AHIEtbQ-tIsBYNp_bZn1PST3Kez8yY5meA |title=docs.google.com;"Stolen Childhood: A Survivor of the Holocaust" |publisher=docs.google.com;McCall’s Magazine |date=August 1994 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/obituaries/142585166_Helga_Newmark__rabbi_late_in_life__dies.html |title=Helga Newmark, rabbi late in life, dies |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/obituaries/142585166_Helga_Newmark__rabbi_late_in_life__dies.html?c=y&page=2 |title=Helga Newmark, rabbi late in life, dies : page 2 |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref> * 2001: [[Angela Warnick Buchdahl]], born in Korea, became the first Asian-American rabbi. She was ordained in America.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.auburnseminary.org/auburnnews/%E2%80%9Ctroublemaker%E2%80%9D-women-honored-receive-ivy-0 |title="Troublemaker" Women Honored, Receive Ivy &#124; auburn |publisher=Auburnseminary.org |date=August 22, 2009 |accessdate=February 9, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725023419/http://www.auburnseminary.org/auburnnews/%E2%80%9Ctroublemaker%E2%80%9D-women